@node "EINLEITUNG" "About the program"
@next "INSTALLATION"
@prev "DANK"

  This program is a Magic The Gathering (TM) tradeable card card
  database. You can search for cards and create card lists.

  If enough people show interest in TUMMY, I'll consider implementing major
  extensions to the application. So, if you want more power, register or at
  least tell me that you are interested!

  TUMMY was developed using GNU C++ and is based on my own class library.
   
@endnode

@node "INSTALLATION" "Program installation"
@next "PROGRAMMSTART"
@prev "EINLEITUNG"

  The installation of T.U.M.M.Y is easy. The program needs several external
  @{"files" link "PROGRAMMTEILE" 0}, however it will find these automatically.
  All you have to do is copy the program's drawer to the place you like.
  @{b}You won't need any assigns or other stupid path-dependent things!@{ub}

  @{u}Notice:@{uu} The files and drawers found in the program directory may
  not be modified or deleted!

@endnode

@node "HILFE" "Getting help"
@next "VERSIONEN"
@prev "PROGRAMMSTART"

  In case you are running into problems: T.U.M.M.Y offers you two ways to
  get help.

  First there's the short help; a fast, one-line tip that offers a hint on
  the function of all windows and gadgets. Apart from that there is also
  the hyperhelp system based on this AmigaGuide document that gives you an
  extended description on all windows, gadgets and menus.

  The short help is built into the program and is always active. @{b}If you
  move the pointer over an active window or a gadget of an active window you
  will see a short description of that item in the title of the screen.@{ub}

  If that isn't enough you can query the hyperhelp. @{b}Again, move the pointer
  over the item of your interest and press the <Help>-key. The respective
  page of this document will be displayed.@{ub}
  
@endnode

@node "PROGRAMMSTART" "Starting the program"
@next "HILFE"
@prev "INSTALLATION"

  @{b}T.U.M.M.Y may be started from both the Workbench and the CLI.@{ub}

  There are no Workbench-tooltypes or CLI arguments needed.

  If something went wrong T.U.M.M.Y will of course notify you of this, however
  if you didn't modify any of the files or paths you shouldn't run into any
  serious problems.
  
@endnode

